{"source_key":"sha256-852da461b9759bc2736926d9891eb9a3","record_index":10078,"record_hash":"sha256:e79a837db9ea386f749d4a9d7dce4110abb215c9e1250ccd925389bd2cf27768","timestamp":"2026-05-20T18:46:45.704Z","kind":"tool_result","source_event_kind":"codex:response_item:function_call_output","role":null,"text":"Chunk ID: dc79e6\nWall time: 0.0000 seconds\nProcess exited with code 0\nOriginal token count: 2596\nOutput:\n\n## Minimal Tool Draft\n\nThe minimal agent-facing surface should be three read tools:\n\n```text\nbut agentlog sessions [branch [<branch>] | review <review> | change <change>] [--limit N]\nbut agentlog timeline <session-key> [--limit N]\nbut agentlog records <session-key> --turn <turn-key> [--from start|end|<index>] [--limit N]\n```\n\nThis is enough for an agent to:\n\n1. discover prior sessions\n2. orient itself in the session and turn structure\n3. read bounded transcript records only where needed\n\nThere should not be a first-class `handoff` command. Handoff is the workflow the\nagent performs with these tools.\n\nIf `branch` is provided without a branch name, it should mean the current branch.\nThat keeps the common prompt easy:\n\n```text\nCheck whether there are prior agent sessions related to this branch and catch up.\n```\n\nThe CLI can keep storage terms like `session_key` and `turn_key` internally, but\nhuman-facing help should prefer `session id` and `turn id`. \"Key\" reads like an\nimplementation detail.\n\n### `sessions`\n\nPurpose: answer \"what sessions should I inspect?\"\n\nTargeted form:\n\n```text\nbut agentlog sessions branch agentlog-turn-storage\n```\n\nUntargeted form:\n\n```text\nbut agentlog sessions --limit 10\n```\n\nThe targeted form returns sessions related to a branch, review, or change. The\nuntargeted form returns recent project sessions. Both should return compact\norientation data.\n\nJSON should include:\n\n- requested target, if any\n- `session_key`\n- `updated_at`\n- `started_at`, if known\n- `turn_count`\n- `record_count`\n- `related_turn_keys`, only for targeted lookup\n- match evidence, not confidence:\n  - `matched_by`, for example `branch_observed`, `review_observed`,\n    `change_observed`, or `explicit_reference`\n  - `matched_turn_keys`\n  - other observed branch/review/change keys, when present\n- source metadata: agents, providers, models, tool versions\n- latest turn key and latest capture timestamp\n- latest user/assist\n[TRUNCATED]\n experiments, or unrelated active\n  worktree noise.\n- We should not require GitButler app APIs for this. CLI plus `but-agentlog`\n  primitives is the right first surface.\n\n## Subagents And Compactions\n\nReal data already shows multiple related sessions for one branch. Some are\nsidecar/subagent review sessions, not the main user thread.\n\nThe handoff layer should not hide these. It should make them legible:\n\n- main-looking sessions: long-running, many incremental turns, latest user asks\n- sidecar-looking sessions: one backfill, review prompt, separate provider\n  session id, often created close together\n- compacted/resumed sessions: may have a new provider session id but overlapping\n  prior conversation context\n\nAvoid hard-coding those labels until the source data supports them. For now,\nexpose enough facts for the consuming agent to decide.\n\n## Non-Goals\n\n- no provider-native resume\n- no generated persistent handoff summary\n- no magic `handoff` command for v1\n- no durable inferred ownership like \"this branch belongs to this session\"\n- no GitButler app API dependency for the first flow\n- no automatic transcript dumping into `but status`\n- no product-specific review browsing payloads\n\n## Open Questions\n\n- Do we need a first-class \"session outline\" primitive in `but-agentlog`, or can\n  it be assembled cheaply from existing reads?\n- Can we reliably capture provider metadata that distinguishes top-level\n  sessions from spawned subagents?\n- Should compaction/resume grouping be a later derived feature, or do we need to\n  store more source metadata now to make it possible?\n- How much transcript text should human-readable output show by default?\n\n## Recommended First Implementation Slice\n\nDo not implement \"handoff\" as one magic command.\n\nFirst add enough generic CLI read commands that an agent or skill can perform the\ncatch-up workflow:\n\n1. enhance `agentlog sessions` so JSON includes session outline fields, not just\n   keys\n2. add a bounded timeline command for one session\n3. add a bounded records command for one turn\n","tool_name":null,"tool_input":null,"source_record":{"timestamp":"2026-05-20T18:46:45.704Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"function_call_output","call_id":"[REDACTED:entropy]"}}}